    "desc": "Welcome to the IZA website",
    "navbar": "COVID-19 Research\nIZA Newsroom\nLogin\nDE\nABOUT\nRESEARCH\nPUBLICATIONS\nEVENTS\nPEOPLE",
    "text": "COVID-19 Research\nIZA Newsroom\nLogin\nDE\nABOUT\nRESEARCH\nPUBLICATIONS\nEVENTS\nPEOPLE\nWe use cookies to provide you with an optimal website experience. This includes cookies that are necessary for the operation of the site as well as cookies that are only used for anonymous statistical purposes, for comfort settings or to display personalized content. You can decide for yourself which categories you want to allow. Please note that based on your settings, you may not be able to use all of the site's functions.\nConfigure consent\nAccept all\nIZA NEWSROOM | DECEMBER 19, 2022\nImmigration or automation?\nLow-skill immigration to Denmark slowed robot adoption\nRead More\nPrevious\nNext\nAt the cutting edge of labor market research\nWith our local team and global network, we conduct pioneering research in labor economics. Our topics cover all facets of the future of work, currently focusing on the socioeconomic consequences of the global COVID-19 pandemic. In-depth empirical research is the foundation of our independent advice provided to policymakers, business, and society. A key objective of our work is to transfer new knowledge from academic science into the public debate. Drawing on the synergies between our in-house research teams and our international network of scholars, IZA has created a unique platform for scientific exchange at the cutting edge of labor market research.\nTopics\nTeams\nProjects\nNetwork\nOur in-house research agenda is made up of four overarching topics: (1) Changing World of Work, (2) Workers of the Future, (3) Sustainable Labor Policies, (4) Work and Social Cohesion.\nMore about our research\nCOVID-19 and Labor Markets\nPublications\nWe offer a wide range of publications that cater to both an academic and a general audience.\nIZA DISCUSSION PAPER\nIZA DP No. 15824 December 2022\nSkills, Parental Sorting, and Child Inequality\nIZA DISCUSSION PAPER\nIZA DP No. 15822 December 2022\nThe Gendered Crisis: Livelihoods and Mental Well-Being in India during COVID-19\nIZA DISCUSSION PAPER\nIZA DP No. 15809 December 2022\nWorker Satisfaction and Worker Representation: The Jury Is Still Out\nPrevious\nNext\nAll Publications\nEvents\nOur ambitious event agenda consists of annual conferences, focused workshops, and weekly seminars. Forthcoming events include:\nCrisis Resilience: The Role of Minimum Income Support and Upstream Systems\nIZA/BMAS Workshop\nJanuary 17, 2023 Online\nAll Events\nPeople at IZA\nWhat has attracted me to IZA are its great working conditions and atmosphere for young international researchers.\nMaria Balgova\nResearch Associate\nAll Researchers\nPrevious\nNext\nAbout IZA\nIZA is a nonprofit research institute and the leading international network in labor economics, comprising more than 1,600 scholars from around the world. This unique combination of in-house research capacity and global network activities enables us to draw on cutting-edge expertise in conducting research projects and providing scientific policy advice. We provide platforms for knowledge exchange and make relevant research findings accessible for policy practitioners and the general public. Established in 1998, IZA is supported by the Deutsche Post Foundation and affiliated with the University of Bonn.\nMore about IZA\nWe support research on labor\nmarkets in low-income countries\n\nPrevious\nNext\nNewsletter\nSubscribe to news from the IZA Newsroom\nand current publications.\nSubscribe\nTwitter\nAlways keep up to date:\nFollow IZA on Twitter.\nFollow\nContact\nForschungsinstitut zur\nZukunft der Arbeit GmbH (IZA)\nSchaumburg-Lippe-Straße 5–9\n53113 Bonn, Germany\niza@iza.org\n+49-228-3894-0\n+49-228-3894-180\nMark Fallak\nPress and Public Relations\nfallak@iza.org\n+49-228-3894-223\nProfile page\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nPrevious\nNext\nImprint\nPrivacy Policy\nCode of Conduct\nStatus\n© 2023 Deutsche Post STIFTUNG",
